This data was calculated using two sources: the{" "} CRISP report from Edmonton (2018) {" "} and{" "} collision data from Saskatoon Police .

The CRISP report breaks down all the costs associated with collisions into three categories:

  • Direct Costs: Expenses such as police, fire, hospital, coroners, and insurance.
  • Human Capital: Economic losses from lost labor, congestion delays, etc.
  • Willingness to Pay (WTP): The cost society is willing to bear to prevent future collisions.

The report provides a granular breakdown, but in simplified terms, the cost matrix looks like this:

Collision Type Direct Costs ($) Human Capital ($) WTP ($)
Injury 48,341 89,408 158,654
Fatality 225,558 2,224,580 6,707,228
Property Damage 14,065 0 0

The report also includes methodologies from Transport Canada and local research to estimate under-reporting. For example, concussions are often linked to property damage reports rather than personal injury reports, since symptoms appear later.

This calculator applies these data points and additional factors to estimate the average cost per day and year, based on the last three years of available reports. Since the last CRISP report was published in 2018, all costs have been adjusted for inflation using a 20.84% increase as per Statistics Canada.

); }
